We need to analyze the buggy function setSelected in OptionGroup. The code:

public void setSelected(Option option) throws AlreadySelectedException
{
    if (option == null)
    {
        // reset the option previously selected
        selected = null;
        return;
    }
    
    // if no option has already been selected or the 
    // same option is being reselected then set the
    // selected member variable
    if (selected == null || selected.equals(option.getOpt()))
    {
        selected = option.getOpt();
    }
    else
    {
        throw new AlreadySelectedException(this, option);
    }
}

The bug: It compares selected (which is a String) with option.getOpt() (the short option key). But when an option is defined with only a long option (no short option), option.getOpt() returns null. So if selected == null, it'll set selected = null (since option.getOpt() is null). Then subsequently, if another option with short opt is attempted, selected is null, so it will allow it (because condition selected == null). But if an option with only long opt is added again, it will set selected to null again, so multiple long-only options can be selected, which is wrong. Also, when comparing with selected.equals(option.getOpt()) where option.getOpt() could be null, it will throw NullPointerException? Actually selected is a String, and if option.getOpt() is null, selected.equals(null) returns false, so that branch goes to else and throws AlreadySelectedException? But the issue is that the selection is based on the option's opt (short form), but long-only options have null opt. So the logic is flawed.

The fix: Instead of using option.getOpt(), we should use option.getKey() which returns the first key (either opt or longOpt). Or we should compare based on the option itself? Usually, OptionGroup.setSelected should track the selected Option object or its key. The common practice is to use option.getKey() which returns the first key (usually the short opt if present, else the long opt). In the Option class, getKey() returns the opt if set, else the longOpt.

Thus the fix: Change selected.equals(option.getOpt()) to selected.equals(option.getKey()).

Also, when setting selected, use option.getKey().

So corrected code:

public void setSelected(Option option) throws AlreadySelectedException
{
    if (option == null)
    {
        selected = null;
        return;
    }
    
    if (selected == null || selected.equals(option.getKey()))
    {
        selected = option.getKey();
    }
    else
    {
        throw new AlreadySelectedException(this, option);
    }
}

